## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024]**
*Define the `this` keyword in Java. Why is it called an implicit reference variable?*

**Model Answer:**
The `this` keyword in Java is a **reference variable** that points to the **current object** — the instance on whose behalf a non-static method or constructor is being executed. It is termed *implicit* because the programmer is **not required to declare it**; the Java compiler automatically injects a `final` reference named `this` of the current class type into every instance method, constructor, and instance initializer. Its primary use is to disambiguate instance variables from local/parameter variables that share the same name (a phenomenon called *shadowing*), to invoke overloaded constructors using `this(args)`, and to return the current object for method chaining.

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
*List any four uses of the `this` keyword with one-line descriptions.*

**Model Answer:**
1. **Disambiguation** — `this.field` differentiates an instance variable from a same-named local variable or parameter.
2. **Constructor chaining** — `this(args)` calls another overloaded constructor of the same class.
3. **Method chaining** — `return this;` enables fluent interfaces by returning the current object.
4. **Argument passing** — A method or constructor can forward the current object via `someMethod(this)`.

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

#### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**[KTU University Exam — Model Paper, KTU 2024 Scheme]**

*(a)* Explain the six different uses of the `this` keyword in Java with suitable code examples. *(7 marks)*

*(b)* Design a Java class `Rectangle` that demonstrates constructor chaining using `this()`. The class should have three constructors — a no-argument constructor (sets length=1, width=1), a one-argument constructor (creates a square), and a two-argument constructor (creates a general rectangle). Include an `area()` method. Show the execution flow. *(7 marks)*

**Model Solution to (a):**

```java
// USE 1: Disambiguate instance variable from parameter
class Employee {
    private String name;
    private int id;
    public Employee(String name, int id) {
        this.name = name;   // this.name → instance, name → parameter
        this.id   = id;
    }
}

// USE 2: Invoke current class method
class Printer {
    void print() { System.out.println("Printing..."); }
    void run()   { this.print(); }   // explicit, equivalent to print();
}

// USE 3: Constructor chaining
class Time {
    int h, m, s;
    Time()              { this(0, 0, 0); }
    Time(int h)         { this(h, 0, 0); }
    Time(int h, int m)  { this(h, m, 0); }
    Time(int h, int m, int s) { this.h = h; this.m = m; this.s = s; }
}

// USE 4: Pass 'this' as method argument
class Logger {
    void log(String msg) { System.out.println(msg + " from " + this); }
    void process()       { App.audit(this); }   // forwards current object
}

// USE 5: Pass 'this' as constructor argument
class Wheel {
    Wheel(Vehicle v) { /* ... */ }
}
class Vehicle {
    private Wheel wheel;
    Vehicle() { this.wheel = new Wheel(this); }   // injection of self
}

// USE 6: Return 'this' for method chaining
class QueryBuilder {
    private String q = "";
    QueryBuilder select(String cols) { this.q += "SELECT " + cols + " "; return this; }
    QueryBuilder from(String table)  { this.q += "FROM "   + table;  return this; }
    String build()                  { return this.q; }
}
// Usage: new QueryBuilder().select("*").from("students").build();
```

**Model Solution to (b):**

```java
class Rectangle {
    private double length, width;

    // (i) No-arg constructor
    public Rectangle() {
        this(1.0, 1.0);                // delegates to (iii)
        System.out.println("Default 1x1 rectangle created.");
    }

    // (ii) Square constructor
    public Rectangle(double side) {
        this(side, side);              // delegates to (iii)
        System.out.println("Square with side " + side + " created.");
    }

    // (iii) General constructor
    public Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width  = width;
        System.out.println("Rectangle " + length + "x" + width + " created.");
    }

    public double area() { return this.length * this.width; }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Rectangle r1 = new Rectangle();          // → triggers chain
        System.out.println("Area: " + r1.area());
    }
}
```

**Execution trace for `new Rectangle();`**

1. `Rectangle()` is invoked.
2. First statement `this(1.0, 1.0);` → control jumps to constructor (iii).
3. (iii) assigns `length=1.0`, `width=1.0` and prints *"Rectangle 1.0x1.0 created."*.
4. Returns to (i), which prints *"Default 1x1 rectangle created."*.
5. Final area calculation: $1.0 \times 1.0 = 1.0$.

---

#### **Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**

**[KTU University Exam — Sample Paper, KTU 2024 Scheme]**

*(a)* What is the `this` keyword? Discuss in detail the use of `this` to resolve variable shadowing and to enable method chaining. Provide a fully working Java program demonstrating both. *(7 marks)*

*(b)* Write a Java class `BankAccount` that uses `this` for all three purposes: (i) disambiguating parameters from instance fields (account holder, balance), (ii) constructor chaining between a no-arg, a name-only, and a full constructor, and (iii) returning `this` from a `deposit()` method to enable chaining. Demonstrate the program in `main()`. *(7 marks)*

**Model Solution to (a):**

The `this` keyword is a **reference to the current object** — the instance that has invoked the method or that is currently being constructed. It is an **implicit, final, instance-level pointer** created by the JVM.

**Shadowing resolution:** When a method or constructor parameter shares the same identifier as an instance field, the local parameter *shadows* the field. Without `this.`, an assignment like `balance = balance;` becomes a no-op. The `this.balance = balance;` form binds the LHS to the instance variable and the RHS to the parameter, correctly storing the value.

**Method chaining:** When a non-void method ends with `return this;`, it hands the same object back to the caller, who can then invoke further methods on it. This is the foundation of the *fluent interface* or *builder pattern*.

```java
class Account {
    private String holder;
    private double balance;

    public Account(String holder, double balance) {
        this.holder  = holder;     // disambiguation
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    public Account deposit(double amt) {
        this.balance += amt;
        return this;               // enables chaining
    }

    public void summary() {
        System.out.println(this.holder + " has " + this.balance);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Account("Anu", 1000)
            .deposit(500)
            .deposit(250)
            .summary();           // → Anu has 1750.0
    }
}
```

**Model Solution to (b):**

```java
class BankAccount {
    private String holder;
    private double balance;

    // (i) No-arg constructor — uses 'this' for chaining
    public BankAccount() {
        this("Unknown", 0.0);
    }

    // (ii) Name-only constructor
    public BankAccount(String holder) {
        this(holder, 0.0);
    }

    // (iii) Full constructor — disambiguates parameters from fields
    public BankAccount(String holder, double balance) {
        this.holder  = holder;     // disambiguation
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // Method that returns 'this' for chaining
    public BankAccount deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) this.balance += amount;
        return this;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Account[" + this.holder + "] = Rs. " + this.balance);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount a1 = new BankAccount();
        BankAccount a2 = new BankAccount("Rahul");

        a1.deposit(1000).deposit(500).show();
        a2.deposit(7500).show();
    }
}
```

**Expected output:**

```
Account[Unknown] = Rs. 1500.0
Account[Rahul] = Rs. 7500.0
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Common Mark-Deductions:**
> 1. Writing `this(args)` anywhere other than the **first line** of a constructor → **−2 marks**.
> 2. Forgetting to use `this.` when parameter and field have identical names → field stays `null` / `0` → **−1 to −2 marks**.
> 3. Trying to reassign `this` (e.g., `this = new Student();`) — produces compile error → **0 marks for that snippet**.
> 4. Using `this` inside a `static` method or `static` block — compile error → **0 marks**.
> 5. Returning `void` from a chaining method and still trying to chain — **−1 mark** for missing return type adjustment.

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **`this` is a reference, not a keyword in the strict reserved-list sense** (though it is reserved in practice); it points to the current object.
- **It is implicitly declared by the JVM** — programmers do not (and cannot) declare it.
- **Its value cannot be changed** (it behaves like a `final` reference).
- **It cannot be used in `static` contexts** because static members are class-level, not object-level.
- **The most common exam use** is *resolving shadowing* when parameters share names with instance fields.
- **Constructor chaining** via `this()` must always be the **first statement** in the calling constructor.
- **Returning `this`** is the building block of the *fluent interface / builder design pattern*.
- **Lambdas** can capture `this` (the enclosing instance) — this is permitted because lambdas are inherently tied to an object context.
- **KTU frequently asks** for the **six uses** as a 7-mark sub-question — memorize them in order: disambiguation, method call, constructor chaining, argument passing, constructor argument, return for chaining.
- **Examiner tip:** Always demonstrate chaining in `main()` with at least two chained calls to prove return-type correctness.
<!-- SECTION_5_END -->

> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
