> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Sub Class

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In Object-Oriented Programming (OOP), a **Sub Class** (also known as a *Derived Class*, *Child Class*, or *Extended Class*) is a class that inherits attributes (data members) and behaviors (member functions) from another class, which is referred to as the **Super Class** (also called *Base Class*, *Parent Class*, or *General Class*). The mechanism that enables the creation of a Sub Class is termed **Inheritance**, one of the four foundational pillars of OOP (alongside *Encapsulation*, *Abstraction*, and *Polymorphism*).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition (OEERT613 - Module 2):**
> A Sub Class represents an *"is-a"* relationship with its Super Class. It extends the functionality of the parent by adding new properties/methods or by overriding (redefining) inherited methods. In **Java**, the `extends` keyword is used; in **C++**, a colon (`:`) followed by an access specifier is used to derive a sub class.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **biological taxonomy**. Consider the class `Animal` (Super Class). It has general properties such as `eat()`, `sleep()`, and `breathe()`. Now consider `Dog` and `Cat` — they are both *types of* animals. So instead of redefining `eat()` and `sleep()` for each, we make `Dog` and `Cat` as **Sub Classes** of `Animal`. They automatically inherit the common behaviors and can add their own specialized ones, like `bark()` for `Dog` or `meow()` for `Cat`.

```java
// Java representation of the analogy
class Animal {                     // SUPER CLASS
    void eat() { System.out.println("Eats food"); }
    void sleep() { System.out.println("Sleeps"); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {         // SUB CLASS
    void bark() { System.out.println("Barks"); }
}
```

The **Dog** is a Sub Class of **Animal**. Any `Dog` object can `eat()`, `sleep()`, AND `bark()` — but the reverse is **not** true: an `Animal` reference cannot `bark()` unless it is explicitly type-cast to `Dog`.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Distinction:** A Sub Class is **not** merely a "subset." It is a *specialized extension*. The Sub Class has access to **all non-private** members of the Super Class, plus its own additions.

### 1.3 Standard Metrics / Notation

| Symbol | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **B** | Base / Super / Parent Class |
| **D** | Derived / Sub / Child Class |
| **ISA** | "Is-A" relationship (D ISA B) |
| **HAS-A** | Composition (not inheritance) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight:** KTU examiners frequently test whether students can correctly distinguish the **"is-a"** (inheritance) relationship from the **"has-a"** (composition/aggregation) relationship. Marks are routinely awarded or lost on this single distinction.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 Structural Breakdown of a Sub Class

A Sub Class declaration follows this structured logic:

1. **Declaration Phase** — The class is declared with an inheritance specifier.
2. **Acquisition Phase** — All accessible (public/protected) members of the Super Class are inherited.
3. **Extension Phase** — The Sub Class adds new data members and/or member functions of its own.
4. **Override Phase** *(optional)* — The Sub Class may redefine any inherited method (dynamic polymorphism).
5. **Construction/Destruction Chain** — When an object of the Sub Class is created, the Super Class constructor executes **first**, followed by the Sub Class constructor. Destruction follows the **reverse order**.

### 2.2 The "Why" and "How" Behind Each Step

- **Why Inheritance?** To promote **code reusability**, **extensibility**, and to model real-world hierarchical relationships.
- **How does Java handle it?** Through the `extends` keyword (single inheritance only for classes).
- **How does C++ handle it?** Through the `:` colon syntax with an access specifier: `class Derived : public Base { ... };`.
- **How is access controlled?** Through access modifiers: `public`, `protected`, `private` (and the *package-private/default* access in Java).

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet — Access Control Matrix

The following table is **the single most-tested concept** on Sub Classes in KTU exams. Memorize it thoroughly.

| Member declared in Super Class | Accessible from Sub Class? | Accessible outside (other classes)? |
|---|---|---|
| `private` | ❌ No (use getters/setters) | ❌ No |
| `default` *(Java only, package-private)* | ✅ Yes (same package) | ✅ Yes (same package only) |
| `protected` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (only in sub classes or same package) |
| `public` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (everywhere) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical Rule:** A Sub Class **CANNOT** access `private` members of its Super Class directly. This is a classic 3-mark question trap. To access private data, the Super Class must provide `public` or `protected` accessor/mutator methods.

### 2.4 Types of Inheritance Involving Sub Classes

| Type | Description | Java Support | C++ Support |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Single** | One Sub Class from one Super Class | ✅ | ✅ |
| **Multilevel** | Chain: A → B → C | ✅ | ✅ |
| **Hierarchical** | One Super, multiple Sub Classes | ✅ | ✅ |
| **Multiple** | One Sub Class from multiple Super Classes | ❌ (interfaces only) | ✅ |
| **Hybrid** | Combination of multiple + hierarchical | ❌ | ✅ |

### 2.5 Constructor Chaining Rule

When a Sub Class object is instantiated:

$$\text{Execution Order} = \text{Super Class Constructor} \rightarrow \text{Sub Class Constructor}$$

In **Java**, if the Super Class has no default (no-argument) constructor, the Sub Class constructor **must explicitly** call `super(...)` as its first statement.

In **C++**, the derived class constructor implicitly invokes the base class's default constructor unless otherwise specified in the initializer list.

### 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **GUI Frameworks** — `JFrame` → `MyFrame` extends JFrame to add custom buttons.
- **Exception Handling** — `Exception` → `IOException` → `FileNotFoundException` (multilevel).
- **Software Architecture** — Framework design where users extend base classes to plug in custom behavior (Strategy, Template Method patterns).
- **Enterprise Systems** — Employee hierarchy: `Employee` → `Manager` → `SeniorManager`.

