## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Worked Example 1 — C++ Style Sub Class Construction

**Problem:** Model a `Vehicle` Super Class and a `Car` Sub Class. Show the construction chain.

**Step 1 — Define the Super Class:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {                       // SUPER CLASS
protected:                            // Accessible by Sub Class
    int wheels;
public:
    Vehicle() {
        wheels = 4;
        cout << "Vehicle constructor called." << endl;
    }
    void display() {
        cout << "Wheels: " << wheels << endl;
    }
};
```

**Step 2 — Define the Sub Class with extension and override:**

```cpp
class Car : public Vehicle {          // SUB CLASS (public inheritance)
private:
    string fuelType;
public:
    Car() : Vehicle() {               // Explicit base call
        fuelType = "Petrol";
        cout << "Car constructor called." << endl;
    }
    void display() {                  // METHOD OVERRIDING
        Vehicle::display();           // Call base version explicitly
        cout << "Fuel: " << fuelType << endl;
    }
};
```

**Step 3 — Main function demonstrating construction order:**

```cpp
int main() {
    Car myCar;                        // Triggers Vehicle() first, then Car()
    myCar.display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step 4 — Output Trace:**

```
Vehicle constructor called.
Car constructor called.
Wheels: 4
Fuel: Petrol
```

### 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Java Single Inheritance with `super` Keyword

```java
class Employee {                                  // SUPER CLASS
    String name;
    double salary;

    Employee(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    double calculateBonus() {
        return salary * 0.10;                     // 10% bonus
    }
}

class Developer extends Employee {                // SUB CLASS
    int projectsCompleted;

    Developer(String name, double salary, int projects) {
        super(name, salary);                      // EXPLICIT super() call - MUST be first line
        this.projectsCompleted = projects;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateBonus() {                     // METHOD OVERRIDING
        return super.calculateBonus() + (projectsCompleted * 500);
    }
}
```

**Mathematical Trace for a Developer with 3 projects and salary ₹50,000:**

$$\text{Base Bonus} = 50000 \times 0.10 = 5000$$

$$\text{Project Bonus} = 3 \times 500 = 1500$$

$$\text{Total Bonus} = 5000 + 1500 = 6500$$

### 3.3 Analytical Matrix — Member Resolution Table

For the `Developer` Sub Class object referenced as `Employee ref = new Developer(...)`:

| Method Called | Binding Type | Which Version Executes? |
|---|---|---|
| `ref.name` (field access) | Static | `Employee.name` (fields are NOT polymorphic) |
| `ref.calculateBonus()` | Dynamic (virtual) | `Developer.calculateBonus()` |
| `ref.projectsCompleted` | Compile-time ERROR | Not visible through `Employee` reference |
| `((Developer) ref).projectsCompleted` | Downcast required | `Developer.projectsCompleted` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner Insight:** In Java, *all instance methods* are virtual by default (except `static`, `final`, and `private`). In C++, you must declare the base method with the `virtual` keyword to enable dynamic dispatch.

### 3.4 Algebraic Notation of the "is-a" Relationship

Using set-theory notation, a Sub Class `D` and Super Class `B` satisfy:

$$D \subseteq B \quad \text{(Sub Class is a subset of Super Class in semantic terms)}$$

For every property `p` belonging to objects of `B`, the property `p` also holds for objects of `D` (possibly with refined values). Formally:

$$\forall x \in D, \; x \in B$$

This means **every Sub Class object IS-A Super Class object**, justifying *upcasting* without explicit casts.

