> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting `super()` in Java** — If the Super Class has only a parameterized constructor and the Sub Class does **not** explicitly call `super(...)`, the program will fail to compile. This is a **favourite trap** in 14-mark programming questions.
> 2. **Missing `virtual` in C++** — Without `virtual`, base-class pointer to derived object will call the **base** version of the method, not the overridden one. Students lose 2–3 marks here.
> 3. **Confusing `private` inheritance with `public` inheritance in C++** — `class D : private B` makes all inherited public members of B become private in D, breaking the "is-a" relationship.
> 4. **Trying to inherit multiple classes in Java** — Java does not support multiple inheritance through classes; it uses interfaces. Writing `class C extends A, B` is an **immediate compile error**.
> 5. **Upcasting vs Downcasting** — Upcasting (Sub → Super) is implicit. Downcasting (Super → Sub) requires an explicit cast and can throw `ClassCastException` in Java if the actual object is not of the target type.

