# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In Object-Oriented Programming, **access specifiers (or access modifiers)** are keywords in object-oriented languages that set the accessibility of classes, methods, and other members. A **protected member** is a class member (data or function) that is declared using the `protected` keyword, making it accessible from within its own class, from any class **derived (inherited) from that class**, but **not** from any unrelated (non-derived) class or function in the general program scope.

The three canonical access levels in OOP are:

| Access Specifier | Same Class | Derived Class | Outside (via object) |
| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| `private` | ✓ | ✗ | ✗ |
| `protected` | ✓ | ✓ | ✗ |
| `public` | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (OEERT613 - Module 2):** Protected members form a critical link in implementing **inheritance-based polymorphism**. They allow a base class to expose internal state to its subclasses while still hiding it from the rest of the application — striking a middle ground between `private` (fully hidden) and `public` (fully visible).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Language-Specific Behaviour:** In **C++**, `protected` members are accessible only within the class and its derived classes. In **Java**, `protected` additionally grants access to other classes within the **same package**, which is a subtle but exam-relevant distinction.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **family-owned business**:

- **Private** members are like the **CEO's personal diary** — only the CEO themselves can read it. Even the children of the CEO cannot access it.
- **Protected** members are like the **company's internal financial records** — the CEO and all his children (heirs / derived classes) can inspect and use them, but a random customer or competitor cannot.
- **Public** members are like the **company's public advertisements** — anyone in the world can see them.

So, **protected = inheritable privacy**. A parent class trusts its child classes enough to share internal data, but does not trust the outside world.

## 1.3 Core Highlights

- **Accessibility domain:** Class itself + all derived classes (any inheritance level deep).
- **Object-level access:** A derived class can access the `protected` members of the base class **only through a derived class object**, not through a base class object. This is a classic KTU exam pitfall.
- **Friend functions / classes:** Can be granted access even to `protected` and `private` members in C++.
- **Default access:** In a `class` declaration in C++, the default access is `private`. In a `struct`, the default is `public`.

> [!TIP]
> **Memory Aid:** Think **"P-P-O"** → **P**rivate: Parent only; **P**rotected: **P**arents and **O**ffspring; **P**ublic: **P**ublicly open to all.
