# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Rules Governing Protected Members (Structured Logic)

The accessibility of a `protected` member is governed by the following rules:

1. **Rule 1 — Intra-class access:** A `protected` member is always accessible from within the member functions of the class in which it is declared.
2. **Rule 2 — Derived class access:** A `protected` member of a base class is accessible from member functions of any class that is **publicly, protectedly, or privately** derived from it.
3. **Rule 3 — Object-scope restriction:** A derived class can access the `protected` members of a base class **only through a pointer or reference of the derived (or further derived) class type**, not through a pointer or reference of the base class type.
4. **Rule 4 — Non-derived outsiders:** Non-derived, non-friend functions and classes in `main()` or any unrelated class **cannot** access `protected` members of any class.
5. **Rule 5 — Same package (Java only):** In Java, `protected` members are also accessible to any class in the **same package** as the declaring class, even if not derived.
6. **Rule 6 — Friend exception (C++ only):** A function or class declared as `friend` of a class can access its `protected` (and `private`) members freely.

## 2.2 Why Protected Members Exist — The "Why" Behind the Concept

- **Encapsulation with controlled extension:** A designer of a base class may want subclasses to use certain internal data structures (e.g., a linked-list node pointer) but does not want general application code to depend on them.
- **Framework design pattern:** Library / framework authors (e.g., Qt, STL, Java Swing) often declare certain methods as `protected` so that user code can subclass and customize behaviour, but cannot call those methods directly on instances.
- **Polymorphic helper methods:** A base class may expose internal hooks (protected virtual functions) to derived classes so that they can override specific steps of an algorithm — the **Template Method Pattern** is built on this.

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Syntax (C++) | Syntax (Java) | Accessible From |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `private` | `private:` | `private` | Declaring class only |
| `protected` | `protected:` | `protected` | Declaring class + derived classes (+ same package in Java) |
| `public` | `public:` | `public` | Everywhere |
| Friend (C++ only) | `friend class B;` | *(N/A)* | The friended function/class |
| Default in `class` | `private` | *(no default)* | — |
| Default in `struct` | `public` | *(no struct in Java)* | — |

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Embedded firmware hierarchies:** A `Device` base class may declare its raw hardware register pointer as `protected`, allowing specific driver subclasses (e.g., `SPIDevice`, `I2CDevice`) to access it, while preventing application code from corrupting the registers directly.
- **GUI frameworks:** Methods like `paintEvent()` in Qt are `protected` — only subclasses re-implement them; user code never calls them directly.
- **Game engines:** An `Entity` base class might expose its position vector as `protected`, so that `Player`, `Enemy`, and `NPC` subclasses can read/write it, but the game loop cannot bypass validation logic.
