# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Analytical Matrix — Access Resolution Table

The following table shows the access level of a base-class member when inherited under each type of inheritance (C++). This is a **high-frequency KTU 14-mark question**.

| Base Member | Public Inheritance | Protected Inheritance | Private Inheritance |
| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| `public` | `public` in derived | `protected` in derived | `private` in derived |
| `protected` | `protected` in derived | `protected` in derived | `private` in derived |
| `private` | Not accessible | Not accessible | Not accessible |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Takeaway:** `private` members are **never** directly accessible to a derived class, regardless of the inheritance type. `protected` members are always accessible to a derived class, but their visibility in the derived class depends on the inheritance mode.

## 3.2 Worked Example 1 — C++ (Classic KTU Pattern)

**Problem:** Demonstrate the use of `protected` members with single-level inheritance.

**Step-by-step solution:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Base {
private:
    int a = 1;          // not accessible to derived
protected:
    int b = 2;          // accessible to derived
public:
    int c = 3;          // accessible everywhere
    void show() {
        cout << "a=" << a << " b=" << b << " c=" << c << endl;
    }
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void accessTest() {
        // cout << a;   //  ERROR — 'a' is private in Base
        cout << "b=" << b << endl;  //  OK — 'b' is protected
        cout << "c=" << c << endl;  //  OK — 'c' is public
    }
};

int main() {
    Base B;
    Derived D;
    D.accessTest();
    // cout << D.b;     //  ERROR — 'b' is not accessible outside the class hierarchy
    cout << "c via object = " << D.c << endl;  //  OK
    return 0;
}
```

**Line-by-line logical explanation:**

- Line `int a = 1;` → Declared `private`, hence the derived class `Derived` **cannot** access it.
- Line `int b = 2;` → Declared `protected`, hence `Derived::accessTest()` **can** read it.
- Line `int c = 3;` → Declared `public`, hence accessible everywhere, including `main()`.
- Line `D.b` in `main()` → **Compile-time error**, because `protected` members are not accessible through an object in a non-derived scope (i.e., `main` is not a member of `Base` or `Derived`).

## 3.3 Worked Example 2 — Demonstrating Rule 3 (Object-Scope Restriction)

This is the **most-missed** KTU question on this topic.

```cpp
class Base {
protected:
    int x = 10;
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void test(Base& ref) {
        // cout << ref.x;   //  ERROR — accessing protected via Base reference
        cout << x;           //  OK    — accessing own inherited copy
    }
};
```

**Derivation of the rule:**

$$
\text{Access via derived-class pointer/reference} \rightarrow \text{Allowed} \checkmark
$$

$$
\text{Access via base-class pointer/reference (in derived class method)} \rightarrow \text{Disallowed} \times
$$

**Reason:** C++ enforces that a derived class can only access `protected` members through an object whose **static type is the derived class (or further)**, not the base class. This prevents a derived class from "borrowing" another unrelated derived-class object to read protected data.

## 3.4 Worked Example 3 — Multi-Level Inheritance Chain

```cpp
class A { protected: int v = 100; };
class B : public A { };          // 'v' is protected in B
class C : public B {
public:
    void show() { cout << v; }   //  OK — protected members propagate
};
```

**Analytical derivation of visibility at each level:**

$$
\text{Level 0 (A)}: \text{protected } v
$$

$$
\text{Level 1 (B, public inheritance)}: v \text{ remains } \text{protected}
$$

$$
\text{Level 2 (C, public inheritance)}: v \text{ remains } \text{protected} \Rightarrow \text{C can access } v
$$

Therefore, a `protected` member is **always inherited and accessible** at any depth of the inheritance chain, provided the inheritance modes do not downgrade it below `protected`.

## 3.5 Worked Example 4 — Java Variation (Same-Package Access)

```java
package edu.ktu.oop;
public class Base {
    protected int data = 50;
}

package edu.ktu.oop;            // SAME package
public class Helper {
    void read() {
        Base b = new Base();
        System.out.println(b.data);   //  OK in Java (same package)
    }
}
```

In Java, since `Helper` is in the same package as `Base`, it can access `data` even though it is **not** derived. This package-level access does **not** exist in C++.
