## Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. `[KTU University Exam — May 2024]`
**What are protected members in C++? How do they differ from private and public members?**

**Model Answer:**

Protected members are class members declared using the `protected` keyword. They are accessible from within the class in which they are declared and from any class derived (inherited) from it, but not from unrelated functions or classes. They differ from `private` members (which are accessible only within the declaring class) and `public` members (which are accessible from anywhere). Protected members are mainly used to allow controlled access for derived classes while preserving encapsulation from the rest of the program.

*(3 marks — clear definition + 1 mark for each contrast)*

---

### Q2. `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`
**Can a derived class access a protected member of the base class through a base-class object? Justify your answer.**

**Model Answer:**

No, a derived class cannot access a protected member of the base class through a base-class object (or a reference/pointer of base-class type). The C++ standard allows access to protected members only through an object whose static type is the derived class (or a class further derived from it). This rule prevents a derived class from accessing the protected members of an unrelated sibling-derived object. However, the inherited copy in the derived object itself is freely accessible.

*(3 marks — correct no/yes + 2 marks for the justification)*

