## Part B — 14-Mark Questions (Module Internal Choice)

### **Question A — `[KTU University Exam — May 2024, Module 2]`**

**(a)** Explain the three access specifiers in C++ with a suitable example program demonstrating how each behaves in inheritance. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** What happens to a `protected` member when a class is inherited publicly, protectedly, and privately? Construct a multi-level inheritance example to prove your answer. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution (a):**

The three access specifiers in C++ are:

1. **`private`** — accessible only within the class where it is declared.
2. **`protected`** — accessible within the class and in all its derived classes.
3. **`public`** — accessible from anywhere in the program.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Parent {
private:
    int pvt = 1;
protected:
    int prot = 2;
public:
    int pub = 3;
    int getPvt() { return pvt; }   //  allowed
};

class Child : public Parent {
public:
    void display() {
        // cout << pvt;            //  ERROR — not accessible
        cout << "protected = " << prot << endl;  //  OK
        cout << "public = " << pub << endl;       //  OK
    }
};

int main() {
    Child c;
    c.display();
    cout << "public via object = " << c.pub << endl;  //  OK
    // cout << c.prot;   //  ERROR
    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
protected = 2
public = 3
public via object = 3
```

**Explanation of each line (7 marks distribution):**
- 1 mark — definitions of three access specifiers.
- 2 marks — well-structured class `Parent` with all three types of members.
- 2 marks — `Child` class demonstrating derived-class access rules.
- 1 mark — `main` showing outside-class access rules.
- 1 mark — output and conclusion.

---

**Model Solution (b):**

When a class is derived, the visibility of inherited members changes based on the inheritance mode:

| Base Member | Public Inheritance | Protected Inheritance | Private Inheritance |
| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| `public` | `public` | `protected` | `private` |
| `protected` | `protected` | `protected` | `private` |
| `private` | inaccessible | inaccessible | inaccessible |

**Multi-level example to prove the rule:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class A {
protected:
    int x = 10;
public:
    int y = 20;
};

class B : public A {
    // x is protected, y is public
};

class C : public B {
public:
    void show() {
        cout << "x = " << x << endl;  //  OK — protected propagates
        cout << "y = " << y << endl;  //  OK — public propagates
    }
};

class D : private A {
    // x becomes private, y becomes private
};

class E : public D {
public:
    void test() {
        // cout << x;   //  ERROR — x is now private in D, not visible to E
    }
};

int main() {
    C c; c.show();
    return 0;
}
```

**Derivation steps (7 marks distribution):**
- 2 marks — the inheritance-visibility table.
- 2 marks — classes A → B → C proving public & protected propagation.
- 2 marks — classes A → D → E proving private inheritance breaks the chain.
- 1 mark — concluding statement.

---

### **Question B — `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Module 2]` (Alternative Choice)**

**(a)** Discuss the rules of accessibility of `protected` members in C++. What restrictions are placed on accessing them through base-class pointers or references? **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Compare access specifiers in C++ and Java. Highlight the role of the `protected` keyword in each language with an example. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution (a):**

The accessibility of `protected` members in C++ is governed by the following rules:

1. A `protected` member is accessible to **member functions and friends** of the class in which it is declared.
2. It is accessible to **member functions and friends** of any **derived class**.
3. It is **not accessible** through a base-class object/pointer/reference inside a derived class member function. Only a derived-class object (or further derived) may be used.
4. It is **not accessible** from `main()` or from any unrelated, non-friend class.

**Restriction on base-class pointer access:**

```cpp
class Base {
protected:
    int val = 100;
};
class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void f(Base& b) {
        // cout << b.val;   //  ERROR: protected accessed via Base reference
        cout << val;          //  OK
    }
};
```

**Reason:** The C++ standard (ISO/IEC 14882 §11.4) restricts protected access to expressions of the form `obj.member` where the **static type of `obj`** is the derived class (or a class derived from it), not the base class. This prevents a derived class `D1` from accessing protected data of an unrelated derived class `D2` via a base reference.

*(7 marks — 3 for the rules list, 2 for the code, 2 for the standard reference / reason)*

---

**Model Solution (b):**

| Feature | C++ | Java |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Keywords | `private`, `protected`, `public` | `private`, `protected`, `public`, (default = package-private) |
| `protected` access | Declaring class + derived classes | Declaring class + derived classes + **same package** |
| Default in class | `private` | package-private |
| `friend` mechanism | Available | Not available |
| Inheritance effect on visibility | Depends on mode (public/protected/private) | All members inherit as declared (no mode change) |
| `struct` vs `class` | `struct` defaults to `public` | No `struct` keyword |

**Example in C++:**
```cpp
class Animal {
protected:
    string name = "Generic";
};
class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void setName(string n) { name = n; }   //  OK
};
```

**Example in Java:**
```java
package edu.ktu.demo;
public class Animal {
    protected String name = "Generic";
}

// Same package, NOT derived
package edu.ktu.demo;
public class Helper {
    void test() {
        Animal a = new Animal();
        System.out.println(a.name);   //  OK in Java (same package)
    }
}
```

**Key difference:** In C++, `protected` access requires inheritance. In Java, package membership is also sufficient.

*(7 marks — 2 marks table, 2 marks C++ example, 2 marks Java example, 1 mark difference conclusion)*

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Mark-Loss Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Confusing "protected = accessible everywhere"** — It is **not** public. You will lose 2–3 marks if you claim that `protected` works like `public` outside the class.
> 2. **Forgetting the object-scope rule** — In a derived-class method, you **cannot** access a protected member through a base-class pointer/reference. This alone is worth 2 marks in 14-mark questions.
> 3. **Ignoring the inheritance mode** — In C++, `protected` under **private inheritance** becomes `private` in the derived class and is then inaccessible to further derived classes. Students often overlook this.
> 4. **Java pitfall** — Do not assume Java's `protected` behaves exactly like C++'s. The **same-package** rule is a frequent trick question.

---

## Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Definition:** `protected` members lie between `private` and `public` in accessibility.
- **C++ rule:** Accessible in the declaring class and in any derived class — **not** in `main()` or unrelated classes.
- **Java rule:** Same as C++ **plus** same-package access.
- **Object-scope rule (C++):** Accessible only through a derived-class (or further-derived) object, never through a base-class object/pointer/reference.
- **Friend functions (C++ only):** Can access `protected` (and `private`) members of the class that declared them as a friend.
- **Inheritance mode effect:** `protected` stays `protected` under public and protected inheritance; becomes `private` under private inheritance.
- **Multi-level chain:** `protected` members propagate through any number of derivation levels as long as no private inheritance downgrades them.
- **Default access:** `class` → `private`, `struct` → `public` (C++); Java class has no default.
- **Encapsulation value:** `protected` is the **designer-to-inheritor contract** — it lets a base-class author grant controlled access to subclasses without exposing internals to the world.
- **Real-world use:** Hardware register access in embedded drivers, framework hook methods (Qt, MFC), and game-engine entity hierarchies all rely on `protected`.
- **Exam mantra:** "**Protected = Parent and Offspring only**."
