## SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

An **abstract class** in Java is a class that is declared using the `abstract` keyword and represents an incomplete blueprint from which concrete (non-abstract) subclasses are derived. It may declare **zero or more abstract methods** — methods that have a signature but no implementation — and it may also contain concrete methods, instance variables, constructors, and static members.

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition (Verbatim Intent):**  
> "A class which is declared with the keyword `abstract` is known as an abstract class in Java. It can have abstract methods (methods without body) as well as concrete methods (regular methods with body). An abstract class cannot be instantiated, but its reference can be created."

An **abstract method** is a method declared with the `abstract` keyword that has **only a signature (declaration)** and **no method body (implementation)**. It is a contract that forces every concrete subclass to provide its own implementation.

```java
abstract class Shape {
    abstract double area();        // abstract method — no body
    void display() {                // concrete method — has body
        System.out.println("Shape");
    }
}
```

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

Imagine a **building architect's master blueprint** for a housing colony.

- The architect draws a blueprint titled *House* that specifies:
  - Every house **must** have a `calculateArea()` (this is the abstract contract).
  - But the architect **cannot** pre-calculate the area — because a *Villa*, an *Apartment*, and a *Cottage* will each compute it differently.
- So the master blueprint is left **incomplete on purpose** — it declares *what* must exist, but not *how*.
- Any builder (subclass) who picks up this blueprint **must complete the missing parts** before constructing (instantiating) the house.

| Real-World Element | Java OOP Counterpart |
|---|---|
| Incomplete master blueprint | `abstract class` |
| “Every house must have area()” | `abstract method` |
| Completed villa/apartment drawing | `concrete subclass` |
| Constructing an actual house | `instantiation` |
| Cannot build from incomplete blueprint | `cannot instantiate abstract class` |

> [!NOTE]  
> **Key Takeaway:** Abstract classes sit **one level above concrete reality** — they capture shared structure and force their children to fill in the details that vary.

### 1.3 Physical / Linguistic Constants in This Topic

- **Keyword:** `abstract` — reserved word in Java.
- **Default accessibility of abstract method:** `public` or `protected` (cannot be `private`).
- **Mandatory rule:** A class with even **one** abstract method **must** be declared `abstract`.
- **Concrete counterpart metric:** A class is *concrete* only when **0 abstract methods** remain in its declaration.

