## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Rules — The “Why” and “How”

#### Rule 1: Declaration Syntax

```java
abstract class ClassName {
    abstract returnType methodName(parameters);   // ends with semicolon, NOT braces
}
```

**Why:** The semicolon terminator (instead of `{}`) tells the compiler that the implementation is **deliberately missing** and must be supplied by subclasses.

#### Rule 2: Instantiation Prohibition

```java
Shape s = new Shape();   // ❌ COMPILE-TIME ERROR
```

**Why:** An abstract class represents an incomplete concept. Allowing `new Shape()` would create an object with undefined behaviour for its abstract methods.

#### Rule 3: Abstract Class Reference → Concrete Object (Upcasting)

```java
Shape s = new Circle(5.0);   // ✅ Valid — polymorphic reference
s.area();                     // Calls Circle's area()
```

**How:** This is **runtime polymorphism via dynamic dispatch**. The reference type is `Shape` (parent), but the actual object is `Circle` (child). Method resolution happens at runtime based on the actual object type.

#### Rule 4: Subclass Obligation

A concrete subclass **must** override **every** inherited abstract method. If it overrides only some, it must itself be declared `abstract`.

**Why:** The compiler enforces the contract so that no concrete object is left with unimplemented behaviour.

#### Rule 5: Constructors Are Allowed

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    Vehicle() { System.out.println("Vehicle created"); }
}
```

**How:** Constructors are invoked by subclasses via `super()`. They let abstract classes **initialize shared state**.

#### Rule 6: `final`, `static`, `private` Cannot Be Abstract

| Modifier Combination | Allowed? | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `abstract` + `final` | ❌ | `final` forbids overriding, `abstract` demands it — contradiction |
| `abstract` + `static` | ❌ | `static` methods are not overridden, but belong to the class |
| `abstract` + `private` | ❌ | `private` methods are not visible to subclasses, so they cannot be overridden |

#### Rule 7: Abstract Class Can Have `main()` Method

```java
abstract class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Abstract class executed");
    }
}
```

**Why:** `main()` is `static`, so it belongs to the class itself — no instantiation is required to run it.

### 2.2 KTU Formula / Rules Sheet (Cheat Table)

| # | Rule / Property | Formula / Syntax | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Abstract class declaration | `abstract class Name { }` | Can have 0 abstract methods too |
| 2 | Abstract method declaration | `abstract type method(params);` | Ends with `;` — **no body** |
| 3 | Cannot instantiate | `new AbstractClass()` ❌ | Compile-time error |
| 4 | Reference variable | `AbstractClass ref = new Concrete();` ✅ | Enables polymorphism |
| 5 | Subclass obligation | All abstract methods **must** be overridden | Else subclass remains `abstract` |
| 6 | Constructor allowed | Yes — invoked via `super()` | For shared state initialization |
| 7 | `static` method allowed | Yes — but cannot be `abstract` | Belongs to class, not object |
| 8 | `final` class cannot be abstract | `final` and `abstract` mutually exclusive | `final` blocks inheritance |
| 9 | Member accessibility | `public`, `protected`, default, `private` (non-abstract) | Abstract methods cannot be `private` |
| 10 | Multiple inheritance via class | ❌ Not allowed in Java | Use interfaces instead |

### 2.3 Engineering Utility

Abstract classes are widely used in:

- **Framework Design:** Spring, Hibernate — define templates with partially implemented logic.
- **GUI Libraries:** `Component`, `Button`, `Canvas` hierarchies in AWT/Swing.
- **Design Patterns:** **Template Method Pattern**, **Factory Pattern**, **Strategy Pattern**.
- **API Design:** Forces developers to follow a contract while allowing custom behaviour.

> [!NOTE]  
> **KTU Examiner Heuristic:** If the question mentions *“partial implementation”* or *“template for subclasses”* — answer with **abstract class**.

