## SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Analytical Walkthrough — Complete Java Demonstration

Below is the **full evolution** of an abstract class hierarchy, step by step.

#### Step 1: Identify the Common Contract

Suppose we need to model geometric shapes. Every shape must have:
- An `area()` — but formula varies.
- A `display()` — but details vary.

**Logical Conclusion:** Declare `area()` as `abstract` (varying), and `display()` as concrete only if a common message exists.

#### Step 2: Declare the Abstract Superclass

```java
abstract class Shape {
    String color;

    Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
        System.out.println("Shape constructor called. Color: " + color);
    }

    abstract double area();          // contract — no body

    void displayColor() {            // concrete — shared behaviour
        System.out.println("Color: " + color);
    }
}
```

**Logic Behind Each Line:**

- `String color;` — instance variable, inherited by all subclasses.
- `Shape(String color)` — constructor initializes `color`; called by subclass via `super(color)`.
- `abstract double area();` — declares contract; **ends with semicolon**, no `{}`.
- `displayColor()` — concrete method, identical for all shapes.

#### Step 3: Create Concrete Subclass — Circle

```java
class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);              // call abstract class constructor
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}
```

**Transition Logic:**

1. `extends Shape` — inherits abstract contract.
2. `super(color)` — invokes parent constructor to set `color`.
3. `@Override double area()` — **mandatory override** of the abstract method; otherwise compile error.

**Mathematical Derivation of Area:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
A_{\text{circle}} &= \pi \cdot r^2 \\
&= 3.14159 \times (5.0)^2 \\
&= 3.14159 \times 25.0 \\
&= 78.5398 \text{ sq. units}
\end{aligned}
$$

#### Step 4: Create Concrete Subclass — Rectangle

```java
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double length, width;

    Rectangle(String color, double length, double width) {
        super(color);
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }
}
```

**Mathematical Derivation of Area:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
A_{\text{rectangle}} &= l \times w \\
&= 10.0 \times 4.0 \\
&= 40.0 \text{ sq. units}
\end{aligned}
$$

#### Step 5: Driver Class — Demonstration of Polymorphism

```java
public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape s1 = new Circle("Red", 5.0);          // upcasting
        Shape s2 = new Rectangle("Blue", 10.0, 4.0); // upcasting

        System.out.println("Circle area: " + s1.area());
        System.out.println("Rectangle area: " + s2.area());

        s1.displayColor();   // inherited concrete method
        s2.displayColor();
    }
}
```

**Output Trace:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Shape constructor called. Color: Red} \\
\text{Shape constructor called. Color: Blue} \\
\text{Circle area: 78.5398} \\
\text{Rectangle area: 40.0} \\
\text{Color: Red} \\
\text{Color: Blue}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Resolution Logic at Runtime:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Reference type} &\rightarrow \text{Shape} \\
\text{Actual object} &\rightarrow \text{Circle (for } s_1\text{), Rectangle (for } s_2\text{)} \\
\text{Method binding} &\rightarrow \text{Dynamic dispatch via JVM} \\
s_1.area() &\Rightarrow \text{Circle.area()} \\
s_2.area() &\Rightarrow \text{Rectangle.area()}
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.2 Analytical Matrix — Common Exam Scenarios

| Scenario | Code Snippet | Result | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|---|
| Direct instantiation | `Shape s = new Shape();` | ❌ Compile error | Abstract class cannot be instantiated |
| Missing override in subclass | `class X extends Shape { }` | ❌ Compile error | X must override `area()` or be declared `abstract` |
| Reference to concrete object | `Shape s = new Circle("Red", 5.0);` | ✅ Valid | Upcasting — polymorphism |
| Abstract + final combination | `abstract final class A { }` | ❌ Compile error | `final` and `abstract` are mutually exclusive |
| Abstract + private method | `abstract private void m();` | ❌ Compile error | Subclass cannot see `private`, so cannot override |
| Concrete subclass with no override | `abstract class A {} class B extends A {}` | ❌ B must be `abstract` | B inherits A's abstract nature |
| Static method in abstract class | `abstract class A { static void m(){} }` | ✅ Valid | Static methods are not polymorphic |

