## SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

### PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

#### **Q1. Define abstract class and abstract method. Can we instantiate an abstract class? Justify. `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

An **abstract class** is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword that may contain abstract methods (without body) as well as concrete methods (with body). It represents an incomplete template for subclasses.

An **abstract method** is a method declared without a body, ending with a semicolon — it only specifies the signature and forces subclasses to provide an implementation.

**No, we cannot instantiate an abstract class.** If we try `Shape s = new Shape();`, the compiler throws an error because abstract classes are incomplete blueprints. They may contain unimplemented methods, and creating an object of such a class would leave behaviour undefined. However, we **can** create a reference variable of an abstract class type that points to a concrete subclass object — this enables runtime polymorphism. **(3 Marks)**

---

#### **Q2. List any four rules that must be followed while using abstract classes in Java. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`**

**Model Answer (3 Marks — 4 × 0.75 ≈ 3):**

1. **Rule of Mandatory `abstract` Keyword:** A class with even one abstract method must be declared `abstract`.
2. **No Direct Instantiation:** Abstract classes cannot be instantiated using `new`.
3. **Subclass Obligation:** Every concrete subclass must override **all** inherited abstract methods, or declare itself as `abstract`.
4. **No `private` or `static` Abstract Methods:** Abstract methods cannot be `private` (invisible to subclasses) or `static` (cannot be overridden). They also cannot be combined with `final`. **(3 Marks)**

