#### **QUESTION A (14 Marks)**

**(a) Explain the concept of abstract class with a suitable example. Discuss why an abstract class cannot be instantiated.** **[7 Marks]** `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`

**Model Solution:**

**Definition:** An abstract class in Java is declared using the `abstract` keyword and serves as a partially implemented blueprint. It can contain both abstract methods (no body) and concrete methods (with body).

**Suitable Example:**

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();          // contract

    void eat() {                     // shared behaviour
        System.out.println("This animal eats food.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Cat meows");
    }
}
```

**Why Abstract Class Cannot Be Instantiated:**

1. **Incomplete Behaviour:** An abstract class may contain abstract methods with no implementation. Creating an object of such a class would lead to undefined behaviour when these methods are called.
2. **Design Intent:** Abstract classes are meant to be **extended**, not used directly. They exist to provide a common template for related subclasses.
3. **Compile-Time Safety:** Java's compiler enforces this rule at compile time, preventing runtime errors. Attempting `Animal a = new Animal();` results in compile error: *"Animal is abstract; cannot be instantiated"*. **(7 Marks)**

---

**(b) Write a Java program to create an abstract class `BankAccount` with abstract method `calculateInterest()`. Derive two subclasses `SavingsAccount` and `FixedDeposit` that override this method. Demonstrate polymorphism using a base class reference.** **[7 Marks]** `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`

**Model Solution:**

```java
abstract class BankAccount {
    String holderName;
    double principal;

    BankAccount(String holderName, double principal) {
        this.holderName = holderName;
        this.principal = principal;
    }

    abstract double calculateInterest();
}

class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {
    double rate = 0.04;

    SavingsAccount(String name, double principal) {
        super(name, principal);
    }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return principal * rate;
    }
}

class FixedDeposit extends BankAccount {
    double rate = 0.07;
    int years;

    FixedDeposit(String name, double principal, int years) {
        super(name, principal);
        this.years = years;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return principal * rate * years;
    }
}

public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount acc1 = new SavingsAccount("Anu", 100000);
        BankAccount acc2 = new FixedDeposit("Rahul", 200000, 3);

        System.out.println("Savings Interest: ₹" + acc1.calculateInterest());
        System.out.println("FD Interest: ₹" + acc2.calculateInterest());
    }
}
```

**Output:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Savings Interest} &= 100000 \times 0.04 = 4000 \\
\text{FD Interest} &= 200000 \times 0.07 \times 3 = 42000
\end{aligned}
$$

**Polymorphism Demonstration:** The reference variable `acc1` is of type `BankAccount` (abstract parent), but it points to a `SavingsAccount` object. At runtime, JVM calls `SavingsAccount`'s `calculateInterest()`. Similarly for `acc2`. This is **dynamic method dispatch**. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### **QUESTION B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**

**(a) Compare abstract class and concrete class. Discuss when to prefer abstract class over interface in Java.** **[7 Marks]** `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2022]`

**Model Solution:**

| Feature | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `class` |
| Abstract methods | Allowed (0 or more) | Not allowed |
| Instantiation | Cannot be instantiated | Can be instantiated |
| Constructors | Allowed | Allowed |
| `final` keyword | Cannot be `final` | Can be `final` |
| Inheritance | Extended by subclasses | Extended (if not `final`) |
| Purpose | Partial abstraction | Full implementation |
| State (variables) | Can hold state | Can hold state |

**When to Prefer Abstract Class Over Interface:**

1. **Shared State Required:** When subclasses share common fields (e.g., `color`, `balance`) that should be inherited.
2. **Partial Implementation:** When you want to provide some default behaviour (concrete methods) but force subclasses to implement specific methods.
3. **Constructor Needed:** When subclasses need a common initialization sequence.
4. **Versioning Stability:** When the API is unlikely to change — adding methods to an abstract class does not break implementing classes, unlike interfaces (pre-Java 8).

Interfaces are preferred when:
- Multiple inheritance of type is needed.
- The contract is purely behavioural with no shared state.
- Unrelated classes need to share a common protocol. **(7 Marks)**

---

**(b) Explain with code how an abstract class can contain constructors, static methods, and final methods. Why are `private` and `static` methods not allowed to be abstract?** **[7 Marks]** `[KTU University Exam – May 2023]`

**Model Solution:**

```java
abstract class Utility {
    static int count = 0;                  // static variable

    Utility() {                            // constructor
        count++;
        System.out.println("Object created. Count: " + count);
    }

    static void showCount() {              // static method
        System.out.println("Total: " + count);
    }

    final void displayType() {             // final concrete method
        System.out.println("This is an abstract class.");
    }

    abstract void perform();               // abstract method
}

class Operation extends Utility {
    @Override
    void perform() {
        System.out.println("Performing operation...");
    }
}

public class UtilityDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Utility.showCount();               // static call without instantiation

        Utility u = new Operation();       // upcasting
        u.perform();
        u.displayType();
    }
}
```

**Why `private` and `static` Cannot Be Abstract:**

1. **`private` + `abstract`:** A `private` method is not visible to subclasses — it cannot be overridden. Since abstract methods **must** be overridden by subclasses, combining `private` with `abstract` creates a contradiction. The compiler rejects it.

2. **`static` + `abstract`:** Static methods belong to the class, not to any instance, and they cannot be overridden (only hidden by redefinition in subclass). Abstract methods require dynamic dispatch — but static methods are resolved at compile time. Hence, the combination is illegal. **(7 Marks)**

