### 🧠 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Abstract class** = incomplete blueprint declared with `abstract` keyword.
- **Abstract method** = method with signature only, no body, ends with `;`.
- **Cannot instantiate** abstract class directly — only concrete subclasses.
- **Subclass obligation:** must override **all** abstract methods or itself be `abstract`.
- **Constructors allowed** in abstract classes (invoked via `super()`).
- **Cannot combine** `abstract` with `final`, `private`, or `static`.
- **Polymorphism:** abstract class reference can point to concrete subclass object.
- **Abstract class vs Interface:** abstract class supports shared state + constructors; interface supports multiple inheritance of type.
- **Template Method Pattern** is the most common real-world use of abstract classes.
- **RTPM (Runtime Polymorphism)** is achieved via dynamic method dispatch using abstract class references.
- **Static methods** in abstract class can be called without instantiation (e.g., `AbstractClass.main()`).
- A class with **zero abstract methods** can still be declared `abstract` to prevent instantiation.
- **KTU Board Tip:** Always include the **formula/justification**, not just code — explain *why* instantiation is disallowed, not merely *that* it is.

