# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Anatomy of an Interface Declaration

```java
access_modifier interface InterfaceName {
    // 1. Constant fields (implicitly public static final)
    int MAX_SPEED = 120;

    // 2. Abstract method (implicitly public abstract)
    void start();

    // 3. Default method (Java 8+) — has a body
    default void honk() {
        System.out.println("Beep!");
    }

    // 4. Static method (Java 8+) — has a body, called via interface
    static void serviceInfo() {
        System.out.println("Service center info");
    }
}
```

## 2.2 The 5 Golden Rules of Interfaces (Board-Exam Favourite)

1. **All methods are `public abstract` by default** — you may omit these keywords.
2. **All variables are `public static final`** — i.e., they are **constants**. You can never have instance variables inside an interface.
3. **A class uses `implements` (not `extends`)** to inherit an interface.
4. **An interface uses `extends` to inherit another interface** (interface-to-interface inheritance is allowed and multi-inheritance is permitted here).
5. **A class must implement *all* abstract methods** of the interface, otherwise the class must be declared `abstract`.

## 2.3 Multiple Inheritance via Interfaces

```java
interface Flyable { void fly(); }
interface Swimmable { void swim(); }

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {
    public void fly()  { System.out.println("Duck flies"); }
    public void swim() { System.out.println("Duck swims"); }
}
```

This solves the **Diamond Problem** because Java resolves ambiguity through the implementing class's mandatory overrides.

## 2.4 Interface Inheritance (Interface Extending Interface)

An interface can extend one or more interfaces using `extends`.

```java
interface A { void showA(); }
interface B { void showB(); }
interface C extends A, B { void showC(); }
```

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Point:** This is the *only* place in Java where **true multiple inheritance** of *type* is allowed freely without the diamond ambiguity, because interfaces carry no implementation (in the pre-default era).

## 2.5 Default Methods (Java 8 Feature)

Default methods let interfaces provide a **concrete implementation** without breaking existing implementing classes. This was added to support **interface evolution** (e.g., adding `forEach` to `Collection` without breaking all custom Lists).

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void start();                 // abstract

    default void stop() {          // default — has body
        System.out.println("Vehicle stopped");
    }
}
```

If two interfaces provide a `default` method with the **same signature**, the implementing class **must override** it to resolve ambiguity.

## 2.6 Static Methods in Interfaces (Java 8)

Static methods in interfaces belong to the interface itself, not to implementing classes. They cannot be inherited. Called using the interface name.

## 2.7 Functional Interfaces & Lambda (Java 8 Bridge)

A **Functional Interface** is an interface with **exactly one abstract method** (SAM — Single Abstract Method). It is the gateway for **lambda expressions** and **method references**.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello(String name);
}

// Lambda implementation
Greeting g = name -> System.out.println("Hello, " + name);
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `@FunctionalInterface` annotation is optional but **instructs the compiler to verify** the SAM rule. KTU often asks students to identify functional interfaces — `Runnable`, `Comparable`, `Comparator`, `ActionListener` are classic examples.

## 2.8 Marker Interfaces

A marker interface has **no methods or constants**. It "marks" a class as having a property. Examples: `Serializable`, `Cloneable`, `Remote`. The JVM gives special treatment to classes marked with them.

## 2.9 KTU Formula Cheat Sheet — Interface vs Class vs Abstract Class

| Feature | **Interface** | **Abstract Class** | **Concrete Class** |
|---|---|---|---|
| Methods | Abstract + Default + Static | Abstract + Concrete | Concrete only |
| Variables | `public static final` only | Any type | Any type |
| Constructor | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Inheritance | `implements` (multiple OK) | `extends` (single only) | `extends` (single) |
| Access Modifiers | Methods are `public` only | Any modifier | Any modifier |
| Instantiation | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| When to use | Capability / Role | "Is-A" partial blueprint | Full implementation |
| Keyword for inheritance | `implements` | `extends` | `extends` |

## 2.10 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **JDBC** — `Connection`, `Statement`, `ResultSet` are interfaces; drivers provide implementations.
- **Collections** — `List`, `Set`, `Map` are interfaces; `ArrayList`, `HashSet`, `HashMap` are their implementations.
- **Dependency Injection (Spring)** — Beans are wired against interfaces, not concrete classes, enabling easy unit testing with mocks.
- **Strategy Pattern** — Algorithms are encapsulated behind a common interface.
- **API Design** — Public-facing APIs expose interfaces to hide internal classes (binary compatibility).
