# Section 3: Step-by-Step Examples & Analytical Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Example A — A Full Interface Lifecycle

**Problem Statement:** Model a payment system where users can pay via Credit Card, UPI, or Net Banking. All payment modes must support `pay(amount)` and `refund(amount)`. Write the interface and at least one implementation.

**Step 1: Define the Interface (the contract)**

```java
public interface PaymentGateway {

    // Constant — transaction fee percentage
    double TRANSACTION_FEE = 2.5;

    // Abstract methods — must be implemented
    void pay(double amount);
    void refund(double transactionId);

    // Default method — common to all gateways
    default void printReceipt(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Receipt: Rs. " + amount + " paid.");
    }

    // Static utility method
    static boolean isValidAmount(double amount) {
        return amount > 0;
    }
}
```

**Step 2: Provide the first implementation**

```java
public class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentGateway {
    private String cardNumber;

    public CreditCardPayment(String cardNumber) {
        this.cardNumber = cardNumber;
    }

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        if (PaymentGateway.isValidAmount(amount)) {
            double fee = amount * PaymentGateway.TRANSACTION_FEE / 100;
            System.out.println("Paid Rs. " + amount + " via Credit Card ending "
                                + cardNumber.substring(cardNumber.length() - 4)
                                + ". Fee: Rs. " + fee);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void refund(double transactionId) {
        System.out.println("Refund initiated for txn " + transactionId);
    }
}
```

**Step 3: Provide a second implementation**

```java
public class UPIPayment implements PaymentGateway {
    private String upiId;

    public UPIPayment(String upiId) {
        this.upiId = upiId;
    }

    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        if (PaymentGateway.isValidAmount(amount)) {
            System.out.println("Paid Rs. " + amount + " via UPI ID " + upiId);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void refund(double transactionId) {
        System.out.println("UPI refund for txn " + transactionId);
    }
}
```

**Step 4: Polymorphic usage in the driver class**

```java
public class Checkout {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PaymentGateway gateway;   // interface reference

        gateway = new CreditCardPayment("1234567812345678");
        gateway.pay(5000.00);
        gateway.printReceipt(5000.00);     // calls default method

        gateway = new UPIPayment("rahul@okbank");
        gateway.pay(1500.00);
    }
}
```

**Output**

```
Paid Rs. 5000.0 via Credit Card ending 5678. Fee: Rs. 125.0
Receipt: Rs. 5000.0 paid.
Paid Rs. 1500.0 via UPI ID rahul@okbank
```

**Step 5: Analytical Reasoning**

$$
\text{Decision: Use Interface over Abstract Class when} \quad
\Big( \text{capability} \neq \text{is-a relationship} \Big)
$$

The payment modes share a **capability** ("can process payments") but they are **not** a "kind-of" entity in a strict taxonomic sense. This is the textbook trigger to choose an **interface** rather than an abstract class.

## 3.2 Example B — Functional Interface with Lambda

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface StringOperation {
    String operate(String s);
}

public class LambdaDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Lambda — implementation of abstract method
        StringOperation upper = s -> s.toUpperCase();
        StringOperation reverse = s -> new StringBuilder(s).reverse().toString();

        System.out.println(upper.operate("ktu"));      // KTU
        System.out.println(reverse.operate("java"));   // avaj
    }
}
```

**Analytical Note:** A functional interface allows the behavior to be *passed around like data* — this is the foundation of **streams**, **callbacks**, and **event handlers** in modern Java.

## 3.3 Example C — Resolving the Diamond Problem with Default Methods

```java
interface Camera { default void snap() { System.out.println("Camera snap"); } }
interface Phone  { default void snap() { System.out.println("Phone snap");  } }

class SmartDevice implements Camera, Phone {
    @Override
    public void snap() {
        Camera.super.snap();   // explicitly pick one
        // OR provide brand-new logic
        System.out.println("SmartDevice snap");
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why this works:** The diamond problem in classes occurs because of shared *state* and constructor chaining. Interfaces (in the Java 8 model) sidestep it by **forcing the implementing class to resolve ambiguity** with an override.

## 3.4 Example D — Interface Extending Multiple Interfaces

```java
interface Readable  { void read();  }
interface Writable  { void write(); }
interface Storage   extends Readable, Writable { void format(); }

class FileSystem implements Storage {
    public void read()   { System.out.println("Reading file");    }
    public void write()  { System.out.println("Writing file");   }
    public void format() { System.out.println("Formatting disk"); }
}
```

**Analytical Flow:**

$$
\text{Storage} \;\xrightarrow{\;\text{extends}\;}\; \text{Readable, Writable}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\text{FileSystem} \;\xrightarrow{\;\text{implements}\;}\; \text{Storage}
$$

A `FileSystem` must implement **all three** abstract methods — those it inherits from `Storage` *and* those that `Storage` aggregates from `Readable` and `Writable`.
