## Part A — Short Answer Questions (2 × 3 = 6 Marks)

### Question 1 (3 Marks) `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`
**Define an interface in Java. Why is it considered a 100% abstract entity?**

**Model Answer:**
An interface in Java is a reference type that can contain only abstract methods, default methods, static methods, and constants (`public static final` variables). It is declared using the `interface` keyword. It is considered a 100% abstract entity because, prior to Java 8, every method declared inside it had no body — it was implicitly `public abstract`. Even after Java 8 introduced default and static methods, the *core purpose* of an interface remains to define a contract without supplying complete implementation, achieving full abstraction.

### Question 2 (3 Marks) `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`
**Differentiate between an abstract class and an interface in Java.**

**Model Answer:**

| Basis | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword for inheritance | `extends` (single only) | `implements` (multiple allowed) |
| Methods | Abstract + concrete | Abstract + default + static |
| Variables | Any type | `public static final` only |
| Constructor | Allowed | Not allowed |
| Access modifiers | Any | Methods are `public` only |
| Use case | "Is-a" partial blueprint | Capability / role contract |

