## Part B — Long Answer Questions (Module Choice, 1 × 14 = 14 Marks)

### 🔹 Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024]`

**(a)** Explain the concept of an interface in Java with a suitable example. Discuss how Java achieves **multiple inheritance** using interfaces. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** What are **default methods** and **static methods** in interfaces (introduced in Java 8)? Write a Java program that demonstrates an interface with both, and explain the **diamond problem** resolution. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution (a)

An interface is a blueprint of a class containing abstract method signatures. A class uses the `implements` keyword to inherit it and must override all abstract methods.

**Multiple Inheritance Example:**

```java
interface Printable { void print(); }
interface Showable  { void show();  }

class Document implements Printable, Showable {
    public void print() { System.out.println("Printing document"); }
    public void show()  { System.out.println("Showing document");  }
}
```

A class can implement **any number of interfaces**, achieving multiple inheritance of *type*. This is safe because the interface carries no instance state or constructor logic — the implementing class resolves all method bodies.

#### Model Solution (b)

**Default methods** provide a default implementation inside the interface, enabling backward-compatible evolution of APIs. **Static methods** belong to the interface itself and are accessed via the interface name.

```java
interface Camera { default void snap() { System.out.println("Camera snap"); } }
interface Phone  { default void snap() { System.out.println("Phone snap");  } }

class SmartDevice implements Camera, Phone {
    @Override
    public void snap() {
        System.out.println("SmartDevice snap");
        Camera.super.snap();   // explicit resolution
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SmartDevice d = new SmartDevice();
        d.snap();
    }
}
```

**Diamond Problem Resolution:** When two interfaces provide a default method with the same signature, the compiler forces the implementing class to override and resolve the ambiguity. The override can call a specific parent's default using `InterfaceName.super.methodName()`.

