### 🔹 Question B (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam – June 2024]`

**(a)** What is a **functional interface**? Explain its role in enabling **lambda expressions** in Java 8 with a suitable example. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Explain the concept of **interface inheritance**. With a suitable Java program, demonstrate an interface extending multiple interfaces, and a class implementing the derived interface. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution (a)

A functional interface is an interface that contains **exactly one abstract method** (SAM — Single Abstract Method). It may contain default or static methods, but only one abstract. The `@FunctionalInterface` annotation is used to enforce this rule at compile time.

Functional interfaces are the *target types* for lambda expressions and method references.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {
    int compute(int a, int b);
}

public class FunctionalDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calculator add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        Calculator mul = (a, b) -> a * b;
        System.out.println(add.compute(10, 20));   // 30
        System.out.println(mul.compute(10, 20));   // 200
    }
}
```

**Role:** Lambdas allow behaviour to be passed as data. Without functional interfaces, anonymous inner classes would be the only option, leading to verbose code. Built-in functional interfaces in `java.util.function` (`Predicate`, `Function`, `Consumer`, `Supplier`) power the Streams API.

#### Model Solution (b)

**Interface inheritance** allows an interface to extend one or more interfaces using the `extends` keyword. Unlike classes, interfaces support **multiple inheritance** of type.

```java
interface Readable { void read();  }
interface Writable { void write(); }
interface Storable extends Readable, Writable {
    void compress();
}

class FileManager implements Storable {
    public void read()     { System.out.println("Reading file");    }
    public void write()    { System.out.println("Writing file");   }
    public void compress() { System.out.println("Compressing file"); }
}
```

**Analytical Note:** `FileManager` is contractually bound to provide implementations of **all** abstract methods — those declared in `Storable` and those inherited transitively from `Readable` and `Writable`. This demonstrates how complex type hierarchies can be composed cleanly in Java.

