## 📌 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid-Revision Checklist)

- An **interface** is a 100% abstract reference type (pre-Java 8) used to define a **contract** of methods a class must implement.
- Declared with the `interface` keyword. Cannot be instantiated.
- **Methods** are implicitly `public abstract` (pre-Java 8). **Variables** are implicitly `public static final`.
- A class uses `implements` to inherit an interface. It **must override all abstract methods** or itself be `abstract`.
- An interface uses `extends` to inherit one or more interfaces (multiple interface inheritance is allowed).
- **Multiple inheritance** of *type* in Java is achieved through interfaces — a class can implement many interfaces.
- **Default methods** (Java 8) have a body and enable interface evolution without breaking implementers.
- **Static methods** in interfaces belong to the interface itself and are not inherited.
- **Functional interface** = exactly one abstract method; used as the target type for **lambda expressions**.
- **Marker interface** = empty interface used to "mark" a class (`Serializable`, `Cloneable`).
- **Interface vs Abstract Class:** Use an interface for a *capability* / role; use an abstract class for a *strong is-a* relationship with shared state or constructor needs.
- All interface method overrides in the implementing class **must be `public`** — a stricter access modifier will not compile.
- The **diamond problem** with default methods is resolved by forcing the implementing class to override the conflicting method, optionally using `InterfaceName.super.methodName()` to call a specific parent's default.
- Interfaces are the foundation of **JDBC**, **Collections Framework**, **Streams API**, and **Dependency Injection** in modern Java — making them one of the most exam-relevant OOP topics in the KTU 2024 syllabus.
