## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Three Mechanisms for Handling Checked Exceptions

The Java language provides exactly **three syntactic mechanisms** for dealing with checked exceptions. Understanding *when* to use each is a high-yield KTU exam topic.

#### Mechanism 1: The `try-catch` Block (Handle In-Place)

The programmer wraps the risky code in a `try` block and provides one or more `catch` blocks to handle specific exception types. This is used when the **current method** has enough context to recover from the failure.

```java
try {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
    // ... use the file ...
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    System.out.println("File missing! Using defaults.");
}
```

#### Mechanism 2: The `try-catch-finally` Block (Handle + Cleanup)

A `finally` block always executes — whether an exception is thrown or not. It is used to **release resources** (close files, database connections, sockets) so that the system never leaks resources.

```java
FileReader fr = null;
try {
    fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
    // ... read the file ...
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot open file.");
} finally {
    if (fr != null) {
        try { fr.close(); } catch (IOException e) { /* swallow */ }
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 High-Yield Fact:** The `finally` block executes even if a `return` statement is encountered inside the `try` block. It also executes if the `try` block completes normally *without* any exception. The **only** situations in which `finally` does NOT execute are: `System.exit()` being called, the JVM crashing, or an `Error` like `OutOfMemoryError` occurring.

#### Mechanism 3: The `throws` Declaration (Propagate Upward)

When the current method **cannot reasonably handle** the exception, it propagates the responsibility to its caller by declaring the exception in the method signature using the `throws` keyword. This is called **ducking the exception**.

```java
public void readConfig(String path) throws FileNotFoundException, IOException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
    // ... read the file ...
}
```

The caller of `readConfig` is now *itself* obliged to either catch these exceptions or re-throw them further up the call stack. This obligation continues all the way up the call chain until either some method handles it or it reaches the `main` method — where, if still unhandled, the JVM prints a stack trace and terminates.

### 2.2 The `throw` Keyword vs. The `throws` Keyword

A frequently tested KTU distinction is between `throw` and `throws`. They look similar but serve completely different purposes.

| **Aspect** | `throw` (verb) | `throws` (declaration) |
|---|---|---|
| **Purpose** | Explicitly **creates and throws** an exception object at runtime | Declares that a method **may pass through** one or more exception types |
| **Where it appears** | Inside a method **body** | In a method **signature** (header) |
| **Number of items** | Throws **exactly one** exception object | Can declare **multiple** exception types, comma-separated |
| **Example** | `throw new IOException("Disk full");` | `public void save() throws IOException, SQLException` |
| **Exception type** | Can be used with both checked and unchecked | Used primarily with checked exceptions |

### 2.3 The Rule of Method Overriding with Checked Exceptions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Favourite Question (Asked in Dec 2021, June 2023):** A subclass overriding a method in the superclass can only declare **the same** checked exceptions or a **narrower** (sub)type of the exception declared in the parent method. It **cannot declare new or broader** checked exceptions. This is the *Liskov Substitution Principle* applied to exceptions.

```java
class Parent {
    public void display() throws IOException { /* ... */ }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    public void display() throws FileNotFoundException { /* VALID — narrower */ }

    // public void display() throws Exception { /* INVALID — broader */ }
    // public void display() throws SQLException { /* INVALID — unrelated */ }
}
```

### 2.4 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet: Checked Exceptions

| **S.No.** | **Property** | **Specification** |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Compiler-enforced?** | **Yes** — enforced at compile-time by `javac` |
| 2 | **Direct superclass** | `java.lang.Exception` (not `RuntimeException`) |
| 3 | **Ultimate superclass** | `java.lang.Throwable` |
| 4 | **Mandatory actions** | Either wrap in `try-catch` OR declare with `throws` |
| 5 | **Recovery typically possible?** | **Yes** — represents external/environmental failure |
| 6 | **Top 5 most-tested examples** | `IOException`, `FileNotFoundException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`, `ParseException` |
| 7 | **Can occur without `throw` statement?** | **Yes** — many are thrown implicitly by JVM (e.g., `ClassNotFoundException`) |
| 8 | **Can be `Error`?** | **No** — `Error` is a separate sibling branch under `Throwable` |
| 9 | **Override rule** | Subclass can declare same or narrower checked exceptions only |
| 10 | **`finally` execution** | Runs even if `try` or `catch` contains `return` statement |
| 11 | **Multi-catch (Java 7+)** | `catch (IOException \vert SQLException e)` allowed for unrelated types |
| 12 | **Custom checked exception** | Extend `Exception` class (NOT `RuntimeException`) |

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

Checked exceptions are indispensable in **enterprise and mission-critical software**:

- **Banking Software (`SQLException`):** Before executing any transaction, the code is forced to consider what happens if the database is unreachable, the network fails, or the SQL syntax is invalid. This prevents silent financial data loss.
- **Web Servers (`IOException`):** Network read/write operations are inherently unreliable. The compiler forces every socket operation to be wrapped, preventing server crashes from unhandled I/O failures.
- **Compiler Tools (`ClassNotFoundException`):** When loading third-party plugins dynamically, the language forces the developer to handle the case where a plugin JAR is missing — preventing the entire IDE or application from crashing.
