**Question 1.** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2022]`

**What are checked exceptions in Java? Give two examples.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Checked exceptions are exceptions that the Java compiler verifies at **compile-time**. They are subclasses of `java.lang.Exception` but are **NOT** subclasses of `java.lang.RuntimeException`. The compiler enforces that any method which may throw a checked exception must either handle it using a `try-catch` block or declare it in the method signature using the `throws` keyword. *(2 marks)*

**Two examples:**
- `IOException` — thrown when an input/output operation fails (e.g., file not found, network error).
- `SQLException` — thrown when a database access error occurs (e.g., invalid SQL, connection failure). *(1 mark)*

---

**Question 2.** `[KTU University Exam - June 2023]`

**Differentiate between `throw` and `throws` keywords in Java.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| **Basis** | `throw` | `throws` |
|---|---|---|
| **Purpose** | Used to **explicitly throw** an exception object | Used to **declare** that a method may pass through exceptions |
| **Location** | Inside the **method body** | In the **method signature** (declaration) |
| **Number of exceptions** | Throws **one** exception at a time | Can declare **multiple** exceptions, separated by commas |
| **Syntax example** | `throw new ArithmeticException("div by 0");` | `void read() throws IOException, SQLException;` |

*(1 mark each row, 3 rows for 3 marks)*

