#### **Question A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam - Model Paper 2024]`

**(a)** Explain the Java exception class hierarchy with a neat diagram. Identify which categories are checked and which are unchecked. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

The Java exception hierarchy is rooted at `java.lang.Throwable`, which has two direct subclasses: `Exception` and `Error`. *(1 mark)*

**`Exception` branch:** Represents conditions that a reasonable application should anticipate and recover from. It is further divided into:
- **Checked exceptions** (subclasses of `Exception` directly, not via `RuntimeException`): The compiler enforces handling. Examples: `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`, `ParseException`. *(2 marks)*
- **Unchecked exceptions** (subclasses of `RuntimeException`): The compiler does **not** enforce handling. Examples: `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`, `NumberFormatException`. *(2 marks)*

**`Error` branch:** Represents serious, abnormal conditions that are external to the application and typically cannot be recovered from (e.g., `OutOfMemoryError`, `StackOverflowError`). The compiler does not enforce catching them. *(1 mark)*

**Diagram:** The student should draw the hierarchy tree with `Throwable` at the top, branching into `Exception` and `Error`, then showing `RuntimeException` under `Exception`, and labelled examples under each category. *(1 mark)*

---

**(b)** Write a Java program that reads a filename from the user and displays its contents. Use proper checked exception handling with `try-catch-finally`. Your program should handle `FileNotFoundException` and `IOException` separately. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class FileDisplay {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter filename: ");
        String filename = sc.nextLine();

        FileReader fr = null;
        BufferedReader br = null;

        try {
            fr = new FileReader(filename);
            br = new BufferedReader(fr);
            String line;
            System.out.println("--- File Contents ---");
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                System.out.println(line);
            }
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("ERROR: File '" + filename + "' does not exist.");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("ERROR: Could not read file. " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            try {
                if (br != null) br.close();
                if (fr != null) fr.close();
                System.out.println("Resources released.");
            } catch (IOException e) {
                System.out.println("Error closing resources.");
            }
        }
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Mark Distribution:**
- Correct imports and class structure *(1 mark)*
- Proper `try` block with file operations *(2 marks)*
- Separate `catch` blocks for `FileNotFoundException` and `IOException` *(2 marks)*
- Correct `finally` block for resource cleanup *(2 marks)*

