## SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Event Handling in Swings** is the mechanism by which a Java GUI application responds to user interactions (such as mouse clicks, key presses, button selections, and window operations). It is implemented using the **Delegation Event Model (DEM)**, in which an **Event Source** (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`) generates an **Event Object** and delegates its handling to a registered **Event Listener** object that implements a specific `XxxListener` interface from the `java.awt.event` package.

According to the **KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus** (Module 4 – Event Driven Programming), event handling is the cornerstone of all interactive Swing-based programs. Without it, a GUI is nothing more than a static, non-responsive drawing.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Hotel Doorbell

Imagine you are staying in a hotel room:

| Hotel Analogy | Java Swing Equivalent |
|---|---|
| The **doorbell button** on the wall | The **Event Source** (e.g., `JButton`) |
| The **electric signal** traveling through the wire | The **Event Object** (e.g., `ActionEvent`) |
| The **hotel receptionist** assigned to ring | The **Event Listener** (e.g., `ActionListener`) |
| The **action** the receptionist takes (bringing towels) | The **Event Handler Method** (`actionPerformed`) |

> [!NOTE]
> The button does **not** decide what to do when clicked. It only "rings the bell" (fires an event). Someone else must be **listening** and respond. This separation of concerns is the heart of the **Delegation Event Model**.

### 1.3 Core Terminology

- **Event Source**: The GUI component that originates an event (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`, `JFrame`).
- **Event Object**: An instance of a subclass of `java.util.EventObject` carrying information about what happened (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`).
- **Event Listener**: An object of a class that implements a listener interface (e.g., `ActionListener`, `MouseListener`).
- **Event Handler Method**: The method defined inside the listener interface that gets executed when the event occurs (e.g., `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`).
- **Delegation**: The act of the source "passing" the event to a registered listener instead of handling it itself.

> [!TIP]
> A source may have **multiple listeners** registered, and **one listener** may be registered to **multiple sources**. The mapping is many-to-many.

