## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Three Participants of Event Handling

The Delegation Event Model involves three mandatory participants. A working program must have **all three** wired together.

#### Participant 1 — Event Source
- A Swing/AWT component object (e.g., `JButton btn = new JButton("Click");`).
- It **fires** events via methods like `addXxxListener(...)`.

#### Participant 2 — Event Listener
- An object whose class **implements** a listener interface (e.g., `implements ActionListener`).
- The interface declares abstract methods that **must** be overridden.

#### Participant 3 — Event Handler Method
- The overridden method that contains the actual response logic.

### 2.2 The Registration Formula

> [!IMPORTANT]
> For an event to be delivered, the listener object **must** be registered with the source using `addXxxListener()`. Without this call, the source has no idea whom to notify.

$$
\text{Source} \xrightarrow{\text{addXxxListener(Listener)}} \text{Event Delivery Enabled}
$$

If you forget this single line, **no event will ever fire** — this is the #1 mistake students make in KTU lab exams.

### 2.3 Event Class Hierarchy

All event classes extend `java.util.EventObject`. Under `java.awt.event`, the major subclasses are:

- `ActionEvent`  → button click, menu selection
- `MouseEvent`   → mouse press, release, click, enter, exit, move, drag
- `KeyEvent`     → key press, key release, key typed
- `WindowEvent`  → window opened, closing, closed, activated, iconified
- `ItemEvent`    → checkbox/radio button/list selection change
- `TextEvent`    → text field content change
- `FocusEvent`   → component gained/lost focus
- `AdjustmentEvent` → scrollbar movement
- `ComponentEvent` → component moved, resized, shown, hidden

### 2.4 Listener Interfaces (The Cheat Sheet)

| Listener Interface | Key Handler Methods | Typical Source Components |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` | `JButton`, `JMenuItem`, `JTextField` |
| `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited` | Any component |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved` | Any component |
| `KeyListener` | `keyPressed`, `keyReleased`, `keyTyped` | Any component |
| `WindowListener` | `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, `windowActivated`, `windowDeactivated`, `windowIconified`, `windowDeiconified` | `JFrame`, `JDialog` |
| `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e)` | `JCheckBox`, `JRadioButton`, `JComboBox` |
| `FocusListener` | `focusGained`, `focusLost` | Any component |
| `TextListener` | `textValueChanged(TextEvent e)` | `TextComponent` subclasses |

### 2.5 Adapter Classes

> [!NOTE]
> Some listener interfaces (like `MouseListener`, `KeyListener`, `WindowListener`) declare **many methods**. If you only care about one, you must still implement all of them (with empty bodies). To avoid this boilerplate, **AWT provides Adapter classes**.

| Adapter Class | Implements |
|---|---|
| `MouseAdapter` | `MouseListener`, `MouseMotionListener`, `MouseWheelListener` |
| `KeyAdapter` | `KeyListener` |
| `WindowAdapter` | `WindowListener`, `WindowStateListener`, `WindowFocusListener` |
| `FocusAdapter` | `FocusListener` |

Adapter classes provide **empty default implementations** for every method. You **override only the methods you need**.

### 2.6 Ways to Provide Listener Implementations

KTU frequently asks this in 7-mark sub-questions. The **four approaches** are:

1. **Implementing the interface in the same class** as the GUI (e.g., `public class MyFrame extends JFrame implements ActionListener`).
2. **Implementing the interface in a separate class** and instantiating it.
3. **Using an inner class** (member or local inner class).
4. **Using an anonymous inner class** — the most common Swing idiom.

### 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

Event handling is the foundation of every interactive software system: ATM interfaces, industrial SCADA dashboards, medical monitoring equipment, mobile apps, web front-ends, and embedded touch interfaces all rely on the same delegation paradigm. Understanding Swing event handling builds the conceptual basis for **JavaFX**, **Android listeners**, and **web DOM event models**.

